<TITLE> Subway project marked for scrutiny </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Jan 7 (bdnews24.com)  The cabinet committee on economic affairs Monday approved a plan to have an underground railway network built by the private sector. The Tk 6,200 crore subway project is meant to ease traffic jams in the capital. The committee, headed by finance and planning adviser Mirza Azizul Islam, decided to send the proposal for scrutiny by the Private Infrastructure Committee (PICOM), which deals with large private sector infrastructure projects. At a meeting in November, communications adviser MA Matin decided to award the contract for building the underground railway system to the most competitive bidder. The provision for constructing an underground railway system was also included in the Strategic Transport Planning for Dhaka which is awaiting government approval. Once built, the 52-kilometre subway will have six routes with 50 stations connecting almost 80 percent of the city area. b
